Let X be a non-empty finite set of points in the plane, and let us define the distance function between two points (x, y) and (a,b) of X as:

dist((x,y),(a,b)) = max(|x−a|, |y−b|)

Show that any continuous function f : X → R can be approximated by a sequence of functions f_n : X → R which are piecewise linear with respect to the above distance function, and whose graphs consist of straight line segments connecting adjacent points in X. In other words, show that for any ε > 0 and any continuous function f : X → R, there exists a function f_n : X → R such that:

1. f_n is piecewise linear with respect to the above distance function;
2. f_n has finitely many linear pieces;
3. f_n and f agree on some dense subset of X;
4. the L∞-norm of f − f_n is less than ε.
